Per-Project Resource Constraints: Limit Ranges
Limit Ranges in OpenShift / Kubernetes (Summary)
1️⃣ Purpose of Limit Ranges
LimitRange is used to control resource usage inside a namespace (project).
While ResourceQuota controls total resources for a namespace, LimitRange controls resource usage for each pod or container.
So:
•	ResourceQuota → Namespace level
•	LimitRange → Pod/Container level
________________________________________
2️⃣ Why LimitRange is Needed
Problems without LimitRange:
•	Users may create pods without CPU/memory limits
•	Pods may consume too many resources
•	Users may forget to set requests and limits
•	Workloads may exhaust namespace quota
LimitRange solves this by:
✅ Setting default values
✅ Enforcing minimum and maximum limits
________________________________________
3️⃣ Example LimitRange Configuration
apiVersion: v1
kind: LimitRange
metadata:
  name: mem-limit-range
  namespace: default
spec:
  limits:
  - type: Container
    default:
      memory: 512Mi
    defaultRequest:
      memory: 256Mi
This means:
Setting	Meaning
default	Default limit applied to containers
defaultRequest	Default resource request
type	Applied to containers
________________________________________
4️⃣ Types of Limits in LimitRange
Default Limit
Applied automatically if the user does not define limits.
Example
default:
 cpu: 500m
 memory: 512Mi
________________________________________
Default Request
Minimum resource guaranteed for a container.
defaultRequest:
 cpu: 250m
 memory: 256Mi
________________________________________
Maximum
Maximum resources allowed for a container.
max:
 cpu: 1
 memory: 1Gi
If a container exceeds this → Pod creation fails
________________________________________
Minimum
Minimum resources required.
min:
 cpu: 125m
 memory: 128Mi
If request is below this → Pod creation fails
________________________________________
Limit-to-Request Ratio
Defines maximum ratio between limit and request.
Example:
ratio = 2
limit <= 2 × request
(Not covered deeply in the course.)
________________________________________
5️⃣ Full Example LimitRange
apiVersion: v1
kind: LimitRange
metadata:
  name: example
  namespace: example
spec:
  limits:
  - type: Container
    default:
      cpu: 500m
      memory: 512Mi
    defaultRequest:
      cpu: 250m
      memory: 256Mi
    max:
      cpu: 1
      memory: 1Gi
    min:
      cpu: 125m
      memory: 128Mi
________________________________________
6️⃣ What Happens When Pod is Created
If deployment has no resource specification:
Kubernetes automatically applies:
Limits:
 cpu: 500m
 memory: 512Mi

Requests:
 cpu: 250m
 memory: 256Mi
These values come from default and defaultRequest.
________________________________________
7️⃣ When Pod Creation Fails
Case 1: Exceeds Maximum
Example:
limit = 1200m
max = 1 CPU
Error:
maximum cpu usage per Container is 1
________________________________________
Case 2: Below Minimum
Example:
request = 100m
min = 125m
Error:
minimum cpu usage per Container is 125m
________________________________________
8️⃣ Important Rules for LimitRange Values
Must follow this order:
max ≥ default ≥ defaultRequest ≥ min
Example valid:
max: 1
default: 500m
defaultRequest: 250m
min: 125m
________________________________________
9️⃣ Important Notes
•	LimitRange does NOT affect existing pods
•	It only affects new pods
•	Admission controller applies it automatically
•	Applies to:
o	Containers
o	Pods
o	PVCs
o	Images
o	ImageStreams
________________________________________
🔟 LimitRange vs ResourceQuota
Feature	ResourceQuota	LimitRange
Scope	Namespace	Pod / Container
Purpose	Limit total resources	Control per-pod resources
Example	total CPU ≤ 8	pod CPU ≤ 1
________________________________________
1️⃣1️⃣ Key Command
Create limit range:
oc create -f limitrange.yaml
Modify deployment resources:
oc set resources deployment example --limits=cpu=500m
________________________________________
1️⃣2️⃣ One-Line Exam Answer
LimitRange is a Kubernetes object that enforces default, minimum, and maximum resource limits for pods or containers within a namespace.

